    <body>
        <sect1>
            <title>Basic Combat</title>

            <para>
                This is a basic introduction to the <tm>Yags</tm>
                combat system, and a description of low tech fighting,
                using swords, bows and brawling. Modern day warfare
                is covered in <em>Modern Combat</em> and futuristic
                combat is covered in <em>Future Combat</em>.
            </para>

            <para>
                <note>It is assumed that the reader has read both the
                Introduction and the Character articles.</note>
            </para>

            <sect2>
                <title>General Terminology</title>

                <para>
                    The following terms are used frequently within
                    these rules, so they are described up front. A
                    full description of how they are used will be
                    given later.
                </para>

                <para>
                    <termlist sort="true">
                        <entry term="Round">
                            A round is a unit of time, averaging
                            about five seconds. Each round, a
                            character has chance to perform a
                            single action - normally an attack or
                            a move. Five seconds is actually quite
                            a long time in a melee fight, so a fair
                            degree of latitude is allowed as regards
                            to what can be accomplished. However,
                            only a single attack may ever be made.
                        </entry>

                        <entry term="Body Levels">
                            Every creature has a number of body
                            levels, which represent their health.
                            Most creatures have a number of body
                            levels equal to their size plus two.
                            The extra two represent <bold>OK</bold>
                            and <bold>Fatal</bold> which are at
                            either extreme of a living creature's
                            state of health.
                        </entry>

                        <entry term="Soak">
                            Soak is how good a creature is at
                            resisting (soaking) damage. An adult
                            human will usually have a base soak of
                            12. Any armour worn adds to this.
                        </entry>

                        <entry term="Wounds">
                            Wounds are serious injuries which have
                            a good chance of causing death. They
                            often puncture the skin, resulting in
                            bleeding and possible the loss of vital
                            organs.
                        </entry>

                        <entry term="Stuns">
                            Stuns are non-serious injuries which
                            result in bruises and pain. They will
                            rarely kill, but a severe beating can
                            in theory inflict enough stuns to kill
                            a person, since excessive stuns translate
                            into <bold>wounds</bold>.
                        </entry>

                        <entry term="Damage">
                            Damage is done when one creature hits
                            another. Often, damage induces wounds or
                            stuns in the target. An attack will
                            inflict either <bold>wounds</bold>,
                            <bold>stuns</bold> or <bold>mixed</bold>
                            damage which is split between stuns and
                            wounds. Many animals cause mixed damage
                            with claw and bite attacks.
                        </entry>

                        <entry term="Load">
                            A character's load is a measure of how
                            much they are carrying. Each weapon and
                            piece of armour has a load associated
                            with it. If the total load is greater
                            than the character's strength x 4, then
                            they are considered to be encumbered and
                            at penalty.
                        </entry>

                        <entry term="Special Attack">
                            A special attack is chosen before
                            initiative is determined, and can have
                            a modifier on how a character attacks,
                            and also on the results of the attack.
                            Individual special attacks are described
                            later, but include such things as killing
                            blow or aimed shot. They are very useful,
                            and players should be aware of their
                            options.
                        </entry>
                    </termlist>
                </para>
            </sect2>

            <sect2>
                <title>Fighting Styles</title>

                <para>
                    When a character or creature makes an attack,
                    they do so using one of a number of different
                    fighting styles. Each fighting style has its
                    own skill, and is independent of the weapon
                    being used.
                </para>
                
                <termlist>
                    <entry term="Brawling">
                        Brawling is the simplest style of fighting,
                        involving punching, kicking and grappling.
                        It also covers use of small weapons such
                        as a knife, dagger or broken bottle. Since
                        the skill of brawling is one of the eight
                        basic talents all people have, everyone has
                        some skill in it. Creatures generally use
                        brawling attacks.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Single weapon">
                        The single weapon fighting style involves using
                        a single one handed weapon to attack with. A
                        shield cannot be used. Most weapons, other than
                        shields and two handed weapons, can be used with
                        this style, and only a single skill (single weapon)
                        is needed to cover them all.
                    </entry>
                    
                    <entry term="Weapon and shield">
                        This fighting style uses a combination of a one
                        handed weapon and a shield, to give what is
                        possibly the best combination. Any type of shield,
                        and any one handed weapon can be used with this
                        style.
                    </entry>
                    
                    <entry term="Great weapon">
                        The great weapon style allows use of a single
                        weapon which requires two hands to use it. It
                        suffers from lack of defence, but such weapons
                        can be very good at cleaving through armour.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Two weapons">
                        This style of fighting involves the use of two one
                        handed weapons at once. Though this gives an edge
                        over only using one weapon, it does not grant two
                        attacks in a combat round. Further, it is
                        generally not as good as using a shield instead
                        of a second weapon, but it does have its advantages.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Longshaft weapon">
                        This style of fighting uses a single two handed
                        weapon such as a long spear, quarterstaff or
                        lance, or single handed versions of the same. A
                        shield may be used if the weapon is one handed.
                    </entry>
                    
                    <entry term="Flail weapon">
                        Flails are a small category of weapon which are
                        quite rare, consisting of a number of balls or
                        rods, attached via chain or leather to a haft.
                        They can be used with or without a shield. They
                        have the advantage that when used defensively,
                        the defence bonus is +10 (rather than +5). If
                        used aggresively, then the attack bonus is +10
                        (rather than +5). See the section of special
                        attacks for more information.
                    </entry>
                </termlist>
            </sect2>

            <sect2>
                <title>Combat Statistics</title>

                <para>
                    Each weapon has a number of statistics which
                    represents how effective it is. These give a bonus
                    to a character's skill checks in combat. All
                    bonuses are zero or positive - no weapon gives a
                    negative adjustment to combat actions.
                </para>
                
                <para>
                    Creatures which have natural attacks have their
                    own combat modifiers, depending on the nature of
                    their natural weapons. Generally, these are worse
                    than those of man made weapons. Size, reach and
                    sharpness all have a say in how effective natural
                    weapons are for a given type of creature.
                </para>

                <termlist>
                    <entry term="Initiative">
                        The initiative of a weapon represents how quickly
                        it can be brought to use. In a round, character's
                        with a high initiative act before those with lower
                        initiatives. Long weapons can grant a high
                        initiative since they provide a tactical advantage
                        for their user.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Attack">
                        The attack rating of a weapon gives a bonus to hit
                        a target. The attacker's attack skill is rolled
                        against the defender's defence skill.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Defence">
                        The defence rating of a weapon adds to a
                        characters parry or dodge attempts. Normally,
                        defence is dexterity based if the character is
                        using a melee weapon, or agility based if not.
                        The single weapon combat style allows the
                        character to choose whether to use agility or
                        dexterity for defence.
                    </entry>

                    <entry term="Damage">
                        The weapon damage adds to the strength of the
                        user, and is unaffected by skill.
                    </entry>
                </termlist>

            </sect2>

        </sect1>


        <sect1>
            <title>Weapons</title>

            <para>
                There are a variety of different weapons, all with their own
                advantages and disadvantages. The table lists the
                most common weapons, together with the statistics which are
                required in combat.
            </para>

            <import-weaponlist href="../equipment/weapons.xml"/>

            <para>
                The four ability modifiers - initiative, attack, defence and
                damage add to the base ability for a character when they are
                using that weapon.
            </para>

            <para>
                The given strength is the minimum strength required to use the
                weapon effectively. If this strength is not met, then the
                character is at -5 to initiative, attack and defence per point
                below. If the weapon is being used two handed, then add 50%
                (round up) to the character's strength for this purpose only.
            </para>

            <para>
                The weapon's load is a measure of how heavy it is. The load of
                all weapons, armour and equipment being carried needs to be
                totalled, and compared to the character's strength, to see if
                they are encumbered. More on this later.
            </para>

            <sect2>
                <title>Using Weapons in Combat</title>

                <para>
                When engaging in combat, a character or creature has five four
                main statistics which govern whether the attack succeeds or
                fails. These are based on the character's skill, with a modifier
                for the weapon.
                </para>

                <skillequation>
                    <title>Initiative</title>
                    <attribute>agility</attribute>
                    <skill>skill</skill>
                    <bonus>weapon initiative bonus</bonus>
                    <die/>
                </skillequation>

                <skillequation><title>Brawl attack</title>
                    <attribute>agility</attribute>
                    <skill>skill</skill>
                    <bonus>weapon attack bonus</bonus>
                    <die/>
                </skillequation>

                <skillequation><title>Melee attack</title>
                    <attribute>dexterity</attribute>
                    <skill>skill</skill>
                    <bonus>weapon attack bonus</bonus>
                    <die/>
                </skillequation>

                <skillequation><title>Missile attack</title>
                    <attribute>perception</attribute>
                    <skill>skill</skill>
                    <bonus>weapon attack bonus</bonus>
                    <die/>
                </skillequation>

                <skillequation><title>Parry Defence</title>
                    <attribute>dexterity</attribute>
                    <skill>skill</skill>
                    <bonus>weapon defence bonus</bonus>
                    <die/>
                </skillequation>

                <skillequation><title>Brawl Defence</title>
                    <attribute>agility</attribute>
                    <skill>skill</skill>
                    <bonus>weapon defence bonus</bonus>
                    <die/>
                </skillequation>

                <skillequation><title>Weapon damage</title>
                    <attribute>strength</attribute>
                    <constant>4</constant>
                    <bonus>weapon damage bonus</bonus>
                    <die/>
                </skillequation>

                <para>
                    An axe for example has an initiative of +6. If
                    the character has a skill of 5 and an agility of
                    3, then their initiative is 5 &#215; 3 (15) + 6 = 21.
                </para>

<para>
Similarly, attack and defence scores are calculated in the same
ways.
</para>

<sect3><title>Shields</title>
<para>
If a character is using a shield, then bonuses from the shield
are added to the bonuses of the primary weapon. This can greatly
bias combat in favour of having a shield. Further, there are other
bonuses gained from using a shield when fighting multiple
opponents, which is described later.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Fighting with Two Weapons</title>
<para>
When fighting with two weapons, the weapon in the off hand is
the secondary weapon, and the other weapon is considered the
primary weapon. Half the statistics (rounded down) of the
secondary weapon are added to those of the primary weapon.
</para>

<para>
Since both weapons give a bonus to damage, this style of
fighting has one advantage over using a shield (which generally
doesn't give any damage bonuses). However, defending with two
weapons isn't as easy as defending with a weapon and shield.
</para>

<para>
The minimum strength requirement of the secondary weapon is
increased by two.
</para>
</sect3>
</sect2>
</sect1>




<sect1><title>Melee Combat</title>
<para>
Strictly speaking, melee combat involves two or more characters
fighting each other close up with melee weapons. The rules for
melee combat form the basis of other forms of combat as well
(such as ranged combat), so the basic rules of combat are
described here.
</para>

<para>
All combat is divided into rounds, and each round is broken
into a number of different steps. Various book keeping activities
happen at the end of each round.
</para>

<sect2><title>The Combat Round</title>
<para>
The sequence of events in each round is as follows. 
</para>

<para>
<orderedlist>
    <listitem><para>
    Determine character actions.
    </para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>
    Roll initiative.
    </para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>
    Perform actions in decreasing order of initiative.
    </para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>
    End of round book keeping.
    </para></listitem>
</orderedlist>
</para>

<sect3><title>Determine Actions</title>
<para>
The first step in each round involves determining what each
character or creature is going to be doing. Since a round lasts
five seconds, there is generally time to move as well as do
something else, though full sprints will take up the entire
round.
</para>

<para>
If a character is performing an attack, then any special attacks
must be declared at this point, before initiative is determined.
</para>

<para>
Action determination is considered to be simultaneous for everyone.
If a character wishes to 'wait' then they must declare what they
are waiting for, and what they will do when it happens. Declarations
such as <emphasis>I'll hit him if he moves</emphasis> are perfectly
valid.
</para>

<para>
It is not possible to wait until the end of the round - any waiting
must be for a particular event. It is not possible to wait for a non
event. For example, an archer might specify that they are waiting for
someone to come through a door, and that they will shoot them when
they do. If someone comes through the door, then they get an attack,
otherwise they perform no action that round.
</para>

<para>
However, a declaration to shoot someone if they come through the door,
otherwise shoot someone else is not valid. The character will not know
that someone is not going to come through the door until the round has
ended, by which time it is too late.
</para>

<sect4><title>Declaring Attacks</title>
<para>
Only one attack may be declared each round by a character. The target
of the attack must be specified, as well as whether the attack is
a special attack of any kind. Many characters may attack a single
target however, up to whatever is practical given the size of the
target. Assume that four people can attack a man sized target, unless
circumstances dictate otherwise.
</para>
</sect4>

<sect4><title>Declaring Defences</title>
<para>
A character may defend against any number of opponents, though there
are penalties if more than one defence is performed. Since defences
are being declared, it is necessary for a character to know who is
attacking them that round.
</para>
</sect4>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Initiative</title>
<para>
Initiative determines who acts first, with higher initiatives going
before lower ones. If the character is making an attack, then their
initiative depends on their initiative derived from their weapon
statistic. Most other actions can be derived from their brawling
initiative (agility x brawl).
</para>

<para>
Some special attacks will modify initiative. An aggressive attack
gives a bonus, a killing blow will mean the character goes last.
If the initiative roll is fumbled, then the character acts last.
</para>

<sect4><title>Who Goes Last?</title>
<para>
Several situations can result in a character <emphasis>going last
</emphasis>. If more than one character is last, then actions are
resolved in the following order.
</para>

<para>
<orderedlist type="1">
    <listitem><para>
    All those not going last act in order of initiative.
    </para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>
    All those who are going last because they fumbled, or who are
    going last because of a special attack but didn't fumble, act in
    order of initiative.
    </para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>
    All those who fumbled when they were already going last (e.g. because
    they tried a killing blow or similar special attack), now act in order
    of initiative.
    </para></listitem>
</orderedlist>
</para>
</sect4>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Perform Actions</title>
<para>
Actions are performed.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>End of Round</title>
<para>
At the end of each round, any general bookkeeping can be performed.
If stamina rolls are needed to remain conscious, then they are made
now.
</para>
</sect3>

</sect2>


<sect2><title>Making an Attack</title>
<para>
If a character chooses to make an attack on someone, then the target
can choose either to defend themselves or not, though this decision
must be made when actions are declared.
</para>

<para>
The attacker makes an attack roll, using their attack rating as follows.
</para>

<para align="center">
attribute x skill + weapon attack bonus + d20
</para>

<para>
If the defender is not defending, then the target difficulty is 15.
If the defender is defending, then they make a defence roll as
follows.
</para>

<para>
attribute x skill + weapon defence bonus + d20
</para>

<para>
If the attack roll is equal to or greater than the defense roll,
then the attack was a success.
</para>

<sect3><title>Multiple Opponents</title>
<para>
A defender who is having to defend against multiple opponents will
be at a penalty to all their defence rolls. It can sometimes be
better to not defend against all attacks, in order to at least have
a chance at defending against some of them. It is not possible to
defend against more than four attacks in a round.
</para>

<para>
