        <row>
            <entry>Damage</entry>
            <entry>Stuns</entry>
            <entry>Penalty</entry>
            <entry>Description</entry>
        </row>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <row>
            <entry>1 - 5</entry>
            <entry>1</entry>
            <entry>+0</entry>
            <entry>Bruised</entry>
        </row>
        <row>
            <entry>6 - 10</entry>
            <entry>2</entry>
            <entry>-1</entry>
            <entry>Dazed</entry>
        </row>
        <row>
            <entry>11 - 15</entry>
            <entry>3</entry>
            <entry>-3</entry>
            <entry>Bloodied</entry>
        </row>
        <row>
            <entry>16-20</entry>
            <entry>4</entry>
            <entry>-6</entry>
            <entry>Battered</entry>
        </row>
        <row>
            <entry>21 - 25</entry>
            <entry>5</entry>
            <entry>-10</entry>
            <entry>Beaten</entry>
        </row>
        <row>
            <entry>26 - 30</entry>
            <entry>6</entry>
            <entry>-15</entry>
            <entry>Oblivious</entry>
        </row>
    </tbody>
</table>
</para>

<para>
Once a character becomes <emphasis>oblivious</emphasis>, they
must make a stamina roll of difficulty 30 or fall unconscious.
Every stun they receive after this requires another stamina
roll, plus the character suffers a single wound.
</para>

<sect3><title>Excess stun damage</title>
<para>
If the number of stuns suffered in a single attack takes the
character beyond the <emphasis>oblivious</emphasis> threshold,
then the excess stuns become wounds, and add to the character's
current wound total.
</para>

<para>
A stamina roll is also required in order to remain conscious.
The target difficulty is increased by 5 for each excess stun.
</para>
</sect3>

</sect2>

<sect2><title>Mixed damage</title>
<para>
Some weapons have a damage type of <emphasis>Mixed</emphasis>,
which causes both stun and wound damage. On a scale of
severity, it isn't as deadly as wound damage, but is worse than
stun damage.
</para>

<para>
Mixed damage is split equally between stuns and wounds, with any
remainder going on stuns (so one level of mixed damage is equivalent
to a single stun).
</para>

<para>
All stuns from mixed damage are cumulative. If a character receives
three levels of mixed damage, he suffers two stuns and one wound.
If that character already has two stuns and two wounds, he will now
have four stuns and three wounds.
</para>
</sect2>

<sect2><title>Fatigue</title>
<para>
Fatigue is not strictly damage, but it is treated in much the same
way as damage is, so is described here. Fatigue is gained due to
strenuous exercise, some mental/magical attacks or lack of sleep.
Depending on the magic system used, spell casting can also result
in fatigue being gained.
</para>

<para>
As for other types of <emphasis>damage</emphasis>, fatigue is
measured in levels, each level giving a penalty to all actions.
These levels range from 'OK' to 'Exhausted'.
</para>
</sect2>

</sect1>


<sect1><title>Armour</title>
<para>
The purpose of armour is to keep someone alive by absorbing or
deflecting the force of a blow away from them. In reality, the
relationship between weapons and armour is complicated, having
evolved during an arms race lasting several millennia. As a type
of armour was developed to counter the weapons then in use, so
the weapons changed to minimise the effects of the new armour.
</para>

<para>
Realistically, it is not always possible to say that one type of
armour is better at stopping damage than another type. The
usefulness of armour depends on whether the attack crushes,
slices or pierces, and there are complications within these as
well. Yags however, deliberately ignores this. Armour has a
single protection value which works equally against all types
of armour.
</para>

<para>
A further simplification is that there are no hit locations.
The protection value of armour also takes into account how
much of the body it covers. It is left to GMs to rule when
an attack can avoid armour - generally this will only be
possible against an unsuspecting foe.
</para>

<sect2><title>Choosing armour</title>
<para>
A full set of armour can consist of several parts, and a character
can mix and match according to preference and finances. Generally,
armour cannot be layered - it is not possible to wear two chain
hauberks at the same time.
</para>

<para>
Each item of armour has a protection value, and a load. The total
load and protection of all worn items is totalled to give the
final value. So, a character wearing soft leather trousers (with
a protection of 2) and a soft leather jacket (also 2), would have
a total armour protection of 4.
</para>

<para>
<variablelist>
    <varlistentry>
        <term>Jacket</term>
        <listitem>Covers the torso, arms and upper thighs.</listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    
    <varlistentry>
        <term>Vest</term>
        <listitem>Covers the torso and shouldres.</listitem>
    </varlistentry>

    <varlistentry>
        <term>Trousers</term>
        <listitem>Covers the legs and lower abdomen.</listitem>
    </varlistentry>

    <varlistentry>
        <term>Helm</term>
        <listitem>Protects the head.</listitem>
    </varlistentry>

    <varlistentry>
        <term>Hauberk</term>
        <listitem>A term used to describe a chainmail jacket. May
        cover the legs down to the knees.</listitem>
    </varlistentry>

    <varlistentry>
        <term>Coif</term>
        <listitem>Covers the head, neck and shoulders. May be
        worn under a helm.</listitem>
    </varlistentry>

    <varlistentry>
        <term>Greaves</term>
        <listitem>Covers the legs. Values given are for a set of
        greaves, one for each leg.</listitem>
    </varlistentry>

    <varlistentry>
        <term>Vambraces</term>
        <listitem>Protects the arms. As for greaves, values given
        assume a set of vambraces.</listitem>
    </varlistentry>

</variablelist>
</para>

<sect3><title>Stacking Armour</title>
<para>
Normally, it is not possible to layer armour on top of other
armour - if it is managed, only the highest protection value
is applied. However, some types of armour are designed to
layer, and in this case the protection values are added
together.
</para>

<para>
Soft leather armour can be worn underneath chain or plate
armour. Plate armour such as greaves, vambraces and breastplates
can be worn over chain armour. It is possible to wear plate
over chain over leather.
</para>

<para>
The other layering combination is that a helm can be worn over
a chain mail coif.
</para>
</sect3>
</sect2>

<sect2><title>Advantages of Armour</title>
<para>
The total protection of all armour worn adds to the soak of the
wearer.
</para>
</sect2>
</sect1>


<sect1><title>Healing and First aid</title>

<sect2><title>First aid</title>
<para>
After a character has become injured, it may be necessary for
first aid to be applied to the wounds in order for them to heal.
Fresh wounds need to be stabilised, a process which requires another
character to make an intelligence x first aid roll on the wounded
character.
</para>

<para>
<table><title>First aid Difficulties</title>
    <colspec colwidth="2cm"/>
    <colspec colwidth="2cm"/>
    <colspec colwidth="1.5cm"/>
    <thead>
        <row>
            <entry>Stuns</entry>
            <entry>Wounds</entry>
            <entry>Target</entry>
        </row>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <row><entry>Bruised</entry><entry>--</entry><entry>0</entry></row>
        <row><entry>Dazed</entry><entry>--</entry><entry>5</entry></row>
        <row><entry>Bloodied</entry><entry>--</entry><entry>10</entry></row>
        <row><entry>Battered</entry><entry>Hurt</entry><entry>10</entry></row>
        <row><entry>Beaten</entry><entry>Light</entry><entry>15</entry></row>
        <row><entry>Oblivious</entry><entry>Medium</entry><entry>15</entry></row>
        <row><entry>--</entry><entry>Serious</entry><entry>20</entry></row>
        <row><entry>--</entry><entry>Critical</entry><entry>20</entry></row>
        <row><entry>--</entry><entry>Fatal</entry><entry>25</entry></row>
    </tbody>
</table>
</para>

<para>
A character may first aid themselves - as long as they are conscious -
but they suffer all their wound penalties. If the first aid roll exceeds
the target difficulty by 10 or more, then not only is the wound
stabilised, but one injury level is immediately healed.
</para>

<para>
If a character is both wounded and stunned, a separate roll is needed for
each. It takes one minute to perform first aid on a person. First aid may
be attempted as many times as required, until it succeeds.
</para>

<para>
A character who is fatally wounded gets a first aid roll before they roll
to see if they die.
</para>
</sect2>

<sect2><title>Natural healing</title>

<sect3><title>Recovering from stuns</title>
<para>
Natural healing can only take place once an injury has been stabilised
with a successful first aid roll. A stunned character who is bruised or
dazed gets a stamina roll every hour at a target difficulty of 20.
Success means that one stun is recovered. If the character spends the
time resting, then the difficulty is reduced to 15. 
</para>

<para>
More serious stun injuries are recovered each night. A similar stamina
roll is made after a night's rest, with success recovering one level
of stun. The severity of the stuns do not affect the recovery difficulty.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Recovering from wounds</title>
<para>
A wounded character who is hurt or lightly wounded gets a stamina
roll after a full night's rest. The stamina difficulty is 20, and
success means one wound level is recovered.
</para>

<para>
A more seriously wounded character gets a recovery roll at the end
of each week. The difficulty depends on the severity of the injury.
</para>

<para>
<table><title>Recovering from wounds</title>
    <colspec colwidth="2cm"/>
    <colspec colwidth="1.5cm"/>
    <thead>
        <row>
            <entry>Wounds</entry>
            <entry>Target</entry>
        </row>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <row><entry>Medium</entry><entry>20</entry></row>
        <row><entry>Serious</entry><entry>25</entry></row>
        <row><entry>Critical</entry><entry>30</entry></row>
        <row><entry>Fatal</entry><entry>35</entry></row>
    </tbody>
</table>
</para>

<para>
If the character fumbles their stamina roll, then their injury
worsens, and they gain an extra wound level. A character who is
already fatally wounded will die.
</para>

<para>
It is not actually possible for a person with average or worse
stamina to recover from being fatally wounded alone. Someone
with the first aid skill can grant a bonus if they spend time
looking after the wounded person. An intelligence x first aid
skill roll is made, and a bonus of +1 per full 5 rolled is
added to the patient's stamina roll.
</para>

<para>
A patient can look after themselves, though they suffer wounds
penalties to do so.
</para>
</sect3>
</sect2>

</sect1>

<sect1><title>Missile Combat</title>
<para>
So far everything that has been covered has dealt with melee
combat between antagonists who are in close combat. The rules
for missile weapons are similar. Unless a difference is noted,
assume that missile combat works the same way.
</para>

<sect2><title>Ranged combat skills</title>
<para>
As for melee combat, there are a number of different styles
which make use of a particular skill.
</para>

<sect3><title>Thrown weapons</title>
<para>
All characters have some ability with the <emphasis>Throw</emphasis>
talent, which is the ranged equivalent of the <emphasis>
Brawl</emphasis> skill. Thrown spears, javelins, bottles, slings and
axes are covered under this skill. This actually covers the
majority of missile combat.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Bow</title>
<para>
The bow, including both the longbow and shortbow, requires this
skill. The bow can be quite a deadly weapon in the hands of a
skilled professional, but can be difficult to use.
</para>

<para>
Both longbows and shortbows are constructed for a given strength
of user. A bow's strength rating is both the minimum and maximum
strength. A stronger bowman cannot use their full strength when
using the weapon.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Crossbow</title>
<para>
Crossbows have their own skill. They are easier to use for the
unskilled user, but don't have the accuracy at long range compared
to the long bow.
</para>
</sect3>

</sect2>

<sect2><title>Missile Ranges</title>
<para>
There are a number of range categories which are defined for
all missile weapons. These are short, medium, long and extreme.
Ranges are given in metres, and cover any distance up to and
including the range given for a particular weapon.
</para>

<para>
<table><title>Range Categories</title>
    <colspec colwidth="1.5cm"/>
    <colspec colwidth="1.5cm"/>
    <colspec colwidth="1.5cm"/>
    <thead>
        <row>
            <entry>Range</entry>
            <entry>Attack</entry>
            <entry>Damage</entry>
        </row>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <row><entry>Short</entry><entry>+0</entry><entry>+0</entry></row>
        <row><entry>Medium</entry><entry>-5</entry><entry>+0</entry></row>
        <row><entry>Long</entry><entry>-15</entry><entry>-5</entry></row>
        <row><entry>Extreme</entry><entry>-30</entry><entry>-10</entry></row>
    </tbody>
</table>
</para>

<para>
The range modifier subtracts from the attacker's attack roll,
making it harder to hit targets at longer range. At long and
extreme range, the damage of a ranged attack is also reduced.
</para>

</sect2>

<sect2><title>Missile Attacks</title>
<para>
If a character declares an attack with a missile weapon, then
they roll initiative as per melee combat, and act in standard
initiative order.
</para>

<sect3><title>Defending with a missile weapon</title>
<para>
One problem with missile weapons is that it is not possible to
parry with them. If the weapon has an equivalent melee defence
total, then use the defence total for that (i.e. a thrown
dagger is treated as a melee dagger for defence), otherwise it
is not possible to parry with a missile weapon. Instead, the
character must perform a brawling defence (agility x brawl),
with no modifier for the weapon being used.
</para>

<para>
Once a thrown weapon has been thrown, any defence bonuses are
lost.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Defending against missile attacks</title>
<para>
Missile attacks can be dodged, but not parried unless the defender
has a shield, in which case they get the defence bonus of the
shield, but not of any other weapon they are using.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Firing into melee</title>
<para>
Firing into a melee combat is rarely a good idea, but sometimes
it is done anyway. If the target of a missile attack is in close
combat with anyone else, then the fumble chance of the attack
is increased by two for each extra person. Firing into a melee
involving six people, would give a +10 to the fumble chance, 
meaning the attacker has a chance of hitting the wrong target if
the d20 rolls less than 12.
</para>

<para>
The chance of fumbling can be modified if the target is much larger
or smaller than the obstructions. This is left for the GM to
decide, but if two humans are fighting a 20m long dragon, then it
is suggested that no penalty is applied.
</para>

<para>
A fumble in this situation means that a random target is hit. It
is possible to hit the 'right' random target. Chance of hitting
each target should be based on size, and ideally distance from
the intended target. In reality, just assigning equal chance to
everyone is good enough.
</para>

<para>
If someone is wrestling with the intended target, add +5 to +15
to the fumble chance, depending on how bad a shot it is. In all
cases, a luck point can be spent before hand to negate, or at
least reduce, the chance of hitting a friend.
</para>
</sect3>

</sect2>

</sect1>

<sect1><title>Advanced Combat</title>

<sect2><title>Special Attacks</title>
<para>
Instead of making a normal attack, before initiative is determined,
a character can opt to make one special attack. Unless noted
otherwise, these are available to all forms of attack, and all
types of weapons. In some cases, special attacks can be combined,
but only if it is specifically noted.
</para>

<sect3><title>Aggressive</title>
<para>
An all out attack is made, giving a +5 bonus to the attack and
initiative rolls, but a -10 penalty to all defence rolls. May 
only be performed with melee attacks.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Aimed Shot</title>
<para>
Only applicable for missile attacks. If an entire round is spent
aiming, then +1 is added to the attacker's perception for the
attack. Spending more than a round aiming does not give further
bonuses, but a <emphasis>killing blow</emphasis> or <emphasis>
ambush</emphasis> may be performed.
</para>
</sect3>


<sect3><title>Ambush</title>
<para>
If the target is unaware of the attack, then an ambush may be
performed. This grants no bonuses to the attack, but the total
soak of the target is halved. Furthermore, then attack counts
as a <emphasis>killing blow</emphasis>. An ambusher cannot
defend during the round, and such an attack is always considered
to be slow.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Cleaving Attack</title>
<para>
A cleaving attack is always slow, and also gives a -10 penalty
to the attack roll, or -5 if a two handed weapon is being used.
If the attack is successful, the armour (not soak) of the target
is halved. Such an attack can only be performed in melee.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Defensive</title>
<para>
If the round is spent fighting defensively, then a +5 bonus
to defence rolls is gained, and a -10 penalty to initiative
and attack rolls. Missile combat is not possible.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Disarm</title>
<para>
This is a melee attack, which can be perform with a melee weapon
against a melee weapon. It cannot be used against shields, and
suffers -10 against a weapon which is being used two handed. A
weapon attack roll is made at -10, versus the defence roll as per
normal (though no defence penalty is suffered from fighting multiple
opponents for this roll only). On success, the defender is off
balance and looses attack and defence bonuses from that weapon for
the rest of the round (it is possible that this has no effect). A
second oppossed roll is made, with the dexterity of the attack and
defender. If the attack equals or exceeds the defender, then the
defender has been disarmed.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Feint</title>
<para>
No attack is made this turn (but character can defend as normal),
and a +5 bonus to attack and initiative is gained next turn, as
long as the same opponent is being fought. Only possible in
melee, and during the following round, any other special attack
can be used. Further, special attacks which automatically go last,
instead act at normal initiative.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Killing blow</title>
<para>
A killing blow is a slow attack, and the character suffers a -10
penalty to the attack roll. If the attack is successful, and at
least two full categories of damage are caused, the target is
instantly killed. If performed with a weapon doing stun or mixed
damage, the target is knocked out instead.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Subduing Attack</title>
<para>
Any attack with a melee weapon can be turned into a subduing
attack, causing stun damage instead of wounds or mixed damage.
</para>
</sect3>

</sect2>

<sect2 status="alpha"><title>Counter attacks</title>

<para>
Counter attacks are designed to make combat slightly more
cinematic. This does not mean unrealistic, but to give a
bit of the flavour of sword fights seen in films.
</para>

<para>
A counter attack is a secondary attack which may be made
against an attacker after a successful defence. It is
secondary because the primary weapon is not used, or if it
is, then only in a minor role. For example, the defender
parries an attackers sword, then kicks them in the stomach,
or bashes them with their shield. As it stands, given that
a character only gets one attack each round, it would be
very inefficient to perform this sort of attack instead of
the primary attack (which is going to have a much higher
chance of being effective).
</para>

<para>
If the defence roll succeeded by 10 or more, then the
defender has the option of performing a counter attack
against the attacker. Whether a counter attack is performed
or not does not affect any other attack or defence rolls
each round. One counter attack may be made per defence -
since multiple defences are penalised already, there is
no further penalty for performing multiple counter attacks.
</para>

<para>
The counter attack is made as a brawling attack, regardless
of the weapon being used. The defender gets a (free) brawling
defence, though if they are already making multiple defences,
then any defence penalty also applies to the brawl defence.
</para>

</sect2>

<sect2><title>Berserkers</title>
<para>
Berserkers are mad warriors who show little concern for their own
survival. Fueled up on bloodlust, religious fervour or drugs, they
are able to shrug aside injuries, and fight with a strength and
ferocity not normally possible.
</para>

<para>
Being a berserker is considered an <emphasis>advantage</emphasis>,
and only characters who have purchased it at character generation
may <emphasis>go berserk</emphasis>.
</para>

<sect3><title>The berserker advantage</title>
<para>
The advantage is purchased to a level, from one upwards. Normally
six is the maximum, though higher levels may be possible through
divine inspiration or magic.
</para>

<para>
If may be possible to increase the level of this advantage over
time, though it may not be improved with experience. Being a
berserker is a mind set which is difficult to learn.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Going berserk</title>
<para>
Going berserk is relatively easy, as long as there is a reason to
fight. No roll is necessary - if there is a fight at hand, and
the character wants to go berserk, then they can do, and they gain
all the bonuses thereof.
</para>

<para>
If there is no-one to fight, then entering a berserk rage is not
possible. There must be the promise of blood letting in the very
near future.
</para>

<sect4><title>Not going berserk</title>
<para>
If a berserker gets involved in a fight in which they do not want
to go berserk, then a will check is required in order to restrain
themselves. Failure means that they go berserk, getting all the
bonuses and penalties associated with that.
</para>

<para>
The difficulty to avoid going berserk is based on the size of the
fight. The bigger and more heroic the fight, the harder it is to
resist going berserk. The character rolls will x 4, at a penalty
of 5 x berserker level.
</para>

<para>
<table><title>Resisting Going Berserk</title>
    <colspec colwidth="5cm"/>
    <colspec colwidth="1.5cm"/>
    <thead>
        <row>
            <entry>Type of fight</entry>
            <entry>Target</entry>
        </row>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <row>
            <entry>A small, friendly fight</entry>
            <entry>0</entry>
        </row>
        <row>
            <entry>Against greatly inferior foe</entry>
            <entry>5</entry>
        </row>
        <row>
            <entry>Against mildly inferior foe</entry>
            <entry>10</entry>
        </row>
        <row>
            <entry>Against similar foe</entry>
            <entry>15</entry>
        </row>
        <row>
            <entry>Against superior foe</entry>
            <entry>20</entry>
        </row>
        <row>
            <entry>Against greatly superior foe</entry>
            <entry>25</entry>
        </row>
    </tbody>
</table>
</para>

<para>
Whether a foe is inferior or superior, depends on the skill of the
foe, as well as numerical superiority.
</para>
</sect4>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Effects of berserk combat</title>
<para>
A berserk warrior must fight the nearest foe to them, and may never
use missile weapons. If there is not a foe in range, then they must
close with the enemy as quickly as possible. A berserker may never
fight defensively.
</para>

<para>
The level of the berserker advantage adds to the attack, initiative
and damage rolls of the berserker. It also subtracts from the
berserker's defence rolls.
</para>

<para>
Any wound, stun or fatigue penalties are reduced by the level of
the advantage. Rolls to stay alive and conscious get a bonus equal
to the advantage.
</para>

<para>
Finally, a berserker gets extra wound and stun levels. These are
temporary and are lost at the end of the battle. One extra wound
and stun level is gained per two full levels of advantage. The first
level is an extra <emphasis>hurt</emphasis> and <emphasis>bruised
</emphasis> level. The second is an extra <emphasis>light</emphasis>
and <emphasis>dazed</emphasis> level. The third is an extra
<emphasis>medium</emphasis> and <emphasis>bloodied</emphasis> level.
</para>

<para>
The real level is lost first when the character is injured, and the
temporary level is lost second. At the end of the fight, the
temporary levels go away, as do any wounds or stuns in them.
</para>
</sect3>

</sect2>

<sect2><title>Mounted combat</title>
<para>
Fighting from horse back can be tricky, but for a skilled rider it
can be a big advantage. If the rider has a riding skill less than
four, then an agility based riding check is required whenever an
attack is made, against a target of 15. A rider with a skill of
four or more does not have to make this roll.
</para>

<para>
Failure of the riding roll means that the character becomes unstable,
and must make a second roll at the same difficulty to remain on the
horse. If the rider is not using saddle and stirrups, then both
difficulties are increased by 5.
</para>

<para>
The character's ride skill adds to all initiative, attack, defence
and damage rolls made while on horseback. For example, a rider with
a skill of 5, gets +5 to all these rolls. No other bonuses due to
being on higher ground etc are gained. The bonuses do apply when
fighting another mounted warrior.
</para>
</sect2>

<sect2><title>Poison</title>
<para>
Use of poison is often frowned upon by honourable warriors, but not
everyone is honourable, and not everyone is a warrior willing to
stand up in a toe-to-toe fight. Poison may be used on darts, put
in food, or put on bladed weapons. Different types of poisons have
varying effectiveness, though very few will give instant death.
</para>

<para>
For a full discussion on the use of poisons, see Herb Lore. However,
some simple poison rules are given here.
</para>

<sect3><title>Resisting Poison</title>
<para>
Any poison may be resisted by making a resistence roll. This is
normally stamina x size of the intended victim.
</para>
</sect3>

<sect3><title>Effects of Poison</title>
<para>
Poison can take a varying amount of time to take affect. This may
be a round, a minute, 15 minutes, a day or any other period of time.
When a poison is first administered, a resistence roll is not made,
instead the roll is made after the given period of time has passed.
Even deadly poisons will tend to have times in the minutes.
</para>

<para>
The target difficulty of the resistence roll is the strength of the
poison. A good poison will tend to have a strength in the 30 - 50 range.
Whether the resistence roll was successful or not, the poison will
continue to do damage to the victim. Once the poison's effect time
has passed again, then another resistence roll is required, at a
reduced difficulty. Normally, the difficulty drops by 5 each time,
though this will be specified in the poison description.
</para>

<para>
For example, a poison with a strength of 40, and a time of 1 minute,
would require a resistence roll against 40 after one minute, against
35 after two minutes, then 30 after three minutes etc. Once 0 or less
has been reached, no further rolls are required and the poison is
considered to have finished its work.
</para>

<sect4><title>When poison works</title>
<para>
If a resistence roll was successful, then the poison has no effect
over that time period. If it failed however, then the victim suffers
some effect from the poison. Poisons will have a number of effects
listed, in increasing order of severity. For example, these might
be nausea, weakness, cramps, paralysis, death.
</para>

<para>
The first time the resistence is failed, the first effect takes
affect. The next failure causes the next effect and so on. For the
above example, for a poison of strength 40, most people are likely
to suffer nausea, weakness and cramps. Many people may suffer
paralysis, and a few would actually die (in worst case, a stamina x
size roll of 20 would need to be failed in order to die).
</para>
</sect4>

</sect3>

</sect2>

